article.description:
Betty Lennox scored 19 points and Pollyanna Johns
Kimbrough had four of her 10 in overtime as the Miami Sol beat the Seattle Storm 65-61 Sunday.
article.headline: All-Star Bird held to season-low six points
article.linkText: Sol rally late, turn back fading Storm in OT
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Betty Lennox scored 19 points and Pollyanna Johns Kimbrough had four of her 10 in overtime as the Miami Sol beat the Seattle Storm 65-61 Sunday. Miami finished the game on a 18-8 run, including eight straight points by Sheri Sam late in regulation. Sam finished with 13 points for Miami (6-10), which is 4-0 all-time against Seattle. "It was a big win for us,'' Lennox said. "We wish it didn't go into overtime, but we're glad that we had another opportunity to capitalize on the mistakes we made throughout the whole game.'' Lauren Jackson had 13 points and 11 rebounds for Seattle, which missed its final nine shots in regulation. Sue Bird had 11 assists, but shot only 2-for-12 and scored a season-low six points for the Storm (8-9). "It's frustrating, because we had the game,'' Seattle guard Michelle Marciniak said. "You've got to be mentally tough and learn how to handle when teams make runs.'' Sam's eight consecutive points came in a span of 1:35 and brought Miami, which trailed by as many as 11 points in the second half, into a 53-53 tie with 3:25 remaining. Neither team scored again in regulation. "I knew Miami wasn't going to quit,'' Seattle coach Lin Dunn said. "We didn't do the job in regulation. We didn't do the job at the free-throw line. We didn't do the job on the boards and we didn't handle their physicalness.'' Kimbrough scored the first four points of overtime to give Miami a 57-53 lead, and the Sol never again trailed. "Great win for us, no question about it,'' Sol coach Ron Rothstein said. "We showed great heart, determination and poise at times. We had a willingness to keep playing and believing that we could get it done.'' Kamila Vodichkova and Marciniak each scored 11 points for Seattle. Seattle finished the first half on an 11-3 run to take a 28-26 lead. Miami took its largest lead of the half, 23-17, on a short jumper by Ruth Riley with 7:10 remaining, but the Sol missed their final seven shots of the half. Miami then missed its first six shots in the second half and Seattle capitalized by scoring nine straight points and go up 37-26 with 17:04 left. Lennox connected on two 3-pointers in a nine-second span to start a 10-2 run that brought the Sol within 45-44 with 9:49 remaining. Seattle, though, scored the next seven points -- including two deep 3-pointers by Marciniak -- to build its lead back to 52-44 with 8:35 remaining. But the Storm missed their next 12 shots, including a 16-footer by Marciniak with three seconds remaining in regulation. "We lost our composure and let them back in the game,'' Bird said. "They turned it up a notch. We stayed at the same level.'' Game notes
Seattle entered the game with the best free-throw shooting percentage in the Western Conference (78.8), but missed seven of 18 from the line in regulation. ... The first 1,500 fans received Lennox bobblehead dolls, although the image is one of Lennox wearing her old Minnesota uniform. ... Sandy Brondello, who had 23 points for Miami against the Storm last season, was 0-for-9 from the field and finished with five points Sunday.
